racing the lives of slaves and owners through multiple records, the author is able to show that the cruelties that slaves faced were not equally shared. One important implication is that internal stratification likely helped perpetuate slavery because there was the belief, however illusionary, that escaping captivity was not necessary for social mobility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aSlaveholderszBrazilzSantos (São Paulo)xSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aSlaveryxSocial aspectszBrazilzSantos (São Paulo)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveszBrazilzSantos (São Paulo)xSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aSocial statuszBrazilzSantos (São Paulo)xHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804778558zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778558423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778558.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles